You can&#39;t do this by using a `SYSTEMTIME` structure, as you have noticed. You need to extract the data from the returned `FILETIME` structure and process that as a 64-bit integer:

    FILETIME fTime;
    GetSystemTimePreciseAsFileTime(&amp;fTime);
    uint64_t ftLo = uint64_t(fTime.dwLowDateTime);
    uint64_t ftHi = uint64_t(fTime.dwHighDateTime);
    uint64_t myTime = ftLo | (ftHi &lt;&lt; 32uLL);

The `myTime` variable will then hold the number of 100 nanosecond intervals since 01-JAN-1601.

To get from this &#39;epoch&#39; value to the &#39;missing&#39; us and ns fields in `SYSTEMTIME` you can simply use the code below. You should also get your own value of milliseconds, in case the conversion to `SYSTEMTIME` has &quot;rounded up&quot; the `dwMilliseconds` value (don&#39;t know if this happens or not):

    uint64_t millis = (myTime % 10000000uLL) / 10000uLL;
    uint64_t micros = (myTime % 10000uLL) / 10uLL;
    uint64_t nanos = (myTime % 10uLL) * 100uLL; // Will have a resolution of only 100ns

*(This works on the assumption that all days since 1/1/1601 have had an integral number of milliseconds, which I think is a reasonable assumption!)*

NOTE: Another option is to copy (or cast) the `FILETIME` struct to a `ULARGE_INTEGER` and then assign the `QuadPart` element of that union to `myTime`. This ***will*** also work but, *in Standard C++, writing to one part of a union and then reading from another is, formally, undefined behaviour.*

